I gotta do a follow up on these @bruntworkwear work boots.  They sent me them mid last year and I have been wearing them 6-7 days a week for the past 15 months.  They are straight up probably the most comfortable boots I have ever had.  Amazing. ⁣
⁣
They are still going strong with the only damage being the eye hooks at the top of the boot popping off.  Couldn’t be more stoked.  Will definitely be getting another pair when these die. ⁣
⁣
Just wanted to post up a long term review as I have been very impressed with these boots and wanted to share my experiences ⁣

Round two on the tire carrier.  Angled the tire to match the barn doors, added some gussets, and bolted the system together. ⁣
⁣
The bottom two bolts are fine thread 1/2” grade 8.  I welded the nuts inside the square tube so fold down will be as easy as hitting two bolts with gun.  Barrel hinge gonna get welded between the two so that whole assembly can fold down. ⁣
⁣
My objective with the rack is to have something to carry the tire when I leave town.  When I get to my destination, tire can come off.  Won’t be folding down the tire all that much so that part isn’t as critical. ⁣
⁣
I just need the space back inside.  38x15.50x18 is a big big tire. ⁣
⁣
#fabrication #welding #mig #sparetire #goprepared #selfsufficient #squarebody #liftedtrucks #squarebodysuburban #builtnotbought #metal⁣

Few more subtle tweaks to the basic carrier that everyone tells me should have been a swing out.⁣
⁣
My solution to bringing a spare on family road-trips.  Without carrying it inside.  Something easy to mount and store and secure and strong. ⁣
⁣
Rattle and bounce free with hitch bracket on receiver.  Safety chains for safety. ⁣
⁣
Fat 2x2 .250 wall square tube slugged and sleeved with 1.5 .120 wall round.  Welded hot with .035, plated, reinforced and strengthened with 1/2” grade8 hardware bolting together. All held together with HD barrel hinge and pin⁣
⁣

After upsetting everyone with my tire hitch I have decided to turn my attention to my winch.  Gonna be hiding a receiver hitch behind the front plate and using this winch mount from the front to the back.  I’ve got power-pole outputs in the rear will just need to run some to the front. ⁣
⁣
Bent up some 3/8” plate and 2x2 .250 tube to make a cradle.  The front needs to be cut back but basic idea is started. ⁣
⁣
Winch is an 8000k warn.  Before I get yelled at in the comments I plan on running a snatch block direct back to the winch on necessary problems and the weight savings over the 12,000k warn are substantial.  That will be appreciated when moving it around. ⁣
⁣

I prefer the ease and utility of a vertical bender and have used my @affordable_bender  to build bumpers and roll cages for several years now. 
⁣
The @roguefab M605 bender has been on my list for a long time.  The @affordable_bender has served me well, and the M605 should help substantially with the new builds I have lined up. ⁣
 ⁣
I chose the unwelded version to save money and because I love welding and finally got it all assembled and ready to go.  The  increased precision and reproducibility this is gonna give me is killer!
⁣
#tubebender #fabrication #rollcage #welding #migwelding #metal #merricksgarage #offroad #roguefab #affordablebender

Started on the front hidden winch mount today.  There is a receiver tucked behind the bumper that the winch mount slides into.  I need to triangulate the mount, paint and add an electrical connection and good to go!⁣
⁣
The mount can be run front or rear and has enough length for the doors to open in the back while it is installed.  Shackle mount off the front to snatch block my door at out of any trouble. ⁣
⁣
Stoked on how this turned out.  Hopefully I don’t need to use it much!⁣
⁣

Double Down is a rare beast.  As a 1991, the K had become a V and the GMT400 body style had been introduced.⁣
⁣
Straddling the generations Double Down has the 18 years of development and refinement from the Squarebody and also some new technology from the 90s. ⁣
⁣
I replaced the transmission with a rebuilt unit and found it interesting that the newest GM had to offer in the 4L80e is paired with the oldest tech in the NP205 transfer case and Detroit diesel. ⁣
⁣
This truck has been a sweet Sunday cruiser.  Overdrive hasn’t worked up until now so I don’t have many miles on it but I am looking forward to some freeways here coming up. ⁣
⁣
Thanks to @loster.duke and @sb_pa for wrestling this big girl back into the truck with me. ⁣
⁣
And thanks to @pivotalmanufacturing manufacturing for the jackstand Dollie’s. Clutch in every heavy situation ⁣
⁣
#gearsfordays #mechanicaladvantage #doubledown #transmission #np205 #heavyduty #squarebody #chevydually #worktruck #merricksgarage #classictruck #forsale

Can’t beat junkyard axles.⁣
⁣
Most of my truck is recycled.  Old vehicle parts refurbished, repaired and put back into service.  The front axle in this truck was dug out of the earth by @fourwheelinnovations out in NY somewhere. The rear axle was junkyard. ⁣
⁣
Took a lot of time and effort, not to mention $$ but I am 100% confident in the axles in the truck and know how to service them hub to hub. ⁣
⁣
Rear axle - 11.5” AAM 4.10 Detroit Locker⁣
Front axle - Dana 60 GM 4.10 Eaton elocker ⁣
 Chromoly axle shaft Yukon hubs⁣

I gotta get a handle on my overheating in the burb.  This is the third trip that has been derailed by overheating. ⁣

Running a big block four row copper and brass radiator from summit with ford windstar fans and shroud.  I had the inlet and outlet upsized to Cummins (2” and 1 3/4)⁣

⁣

The challenge at hand.  Limited space between intercooler and engine.  Adding a large @deraleperformance oil cooler which will be mounted under the truck. If that doesn’t work, the AC condenser will be relocated also.  #problemsolver #overheating #cummins #chummins #dieselpower #hrsprs

Really stoked that so far this tool is living up to my expectations in terms of speed, power, and torque. ⁣
⁣
The pass through design is really nice for long runs of nuts that a deep socket can’t run, like compression hose clamp on intercooler. The custom “sockets” for this tool lock into the head quickly and easily. ⁣
⁣
The direction change is easier to do with a thumb than the traditional dial although it has frozen up on me once.  Quick solution was to just install socket from other side of ratchet to effectively change direction. ⁣
⁣
I would expect this to be the quality I have come to expect from Milwaukee but if longevity or strength is an issue I’ll post again! ⁣
⁣
